I've introduced a new meson option to optionally set the logging-level ('debug' if not set) like
   -Dbmcweb-logging-level=<level>. 
   <level> can be either 'debug', 'info', 'warning', 'error', or 'critical'.

The logging-level will be used if bmcweb-logging is enabled.
For example, if error/critical traces are needed, it can be specified like
   -Dbmcweb-logging=enabled
   -Dbmcweb-logging-level=error

In addition to this addition, I've optimized Logger class by using 'constexpr' so that the only enabled logging codes are emitted to the binary.



    constexpr static bool isLoggingEnabled()
    {
#ifdef BMCWEB_ENABLE_LOGGING
        return true;
#else
        return false;
#endif
    }

    constexpr static LogLevel getCurrentLogLevel()
    {
#ifdef BMCWEB_LOGGING_LEVEL
        return static_cast<crow::LogLevel>(BMCWEB_LOGGING_LEVEL);
#else
        return crow::LogLevel::Debug;
#endif
    }


    constexpr static bool checkLoggingLevel(const LogLevel level)
    {
        return isLoggingEnabled() && (getCurrentLogLevel() <= level);
    }


// NOLINTNEXTLINE(cppcoreguidelines-macro-usage)
#define BMCWEB_LOG_CRITICAL                                                    \
    if constexpr (crow::Logger::checkLoggingLevel(crow::LogLevel::Critical))	\
    crow::Logger("CRITICAL", __FILE__, __LINE__, crow::LogLevel::Critical)

I've decided to take a little more conservative approach so that setLogLevel() can be set at the runtime.
- If -Dbmcweb-logging is not set, or set to 'disabled', no logging will occur.
   In addition, the log routines will not be included in a binary (via if constexpr method).

- If -Dbmcweb-logging is set to a value like 'debug', 'info', 'warning', 'error', 'critical', all log code routines will be included into an executable object.


```
    constexpr static bool isLoggingEnabled()
    {
#ifdef BMCWEB_ENABLE_LOGGING
        return true;
#else
        return false;
#endif
    }
```

```
    static void setLogLevel(LogLevel level)
    {
        getLogLevelRef() = level;
    }

    static LogLevel getCurrentLogLevel()
    {
        return getLogLevelRef();
    }

    static bool checkLoggingLevel(const LogLevel level)
    {
        return getCurrentLogLevel() <= level;
    }
```

And then use these primitives for the logging calls like

```
// NOLINTNEXTLINE(cppcoreguidelines-macro-usage)
#define BMCWEB_LOG_WARNING                                                     \
    if constexpr (crow::Logger::isLoggingEnabled())                            \
        if (crow::Logger::checkLoggingLevel(crow::LogLevel::Warning))          \
    crow::Logger("WARNING", __FILE__, __LINE__, crow::LogLevel::Warning)
```

If #ifdef is false, the the previous code is doing no-op inside if() clause like
```
if (level >= getCurrentLogLevel())
{
   // no-open
}
```

This is essentially equivalent to no-op, and thus move #ifdef to above if().

However, going toward the direction of constexpr, it will become a mute point.

In the original code, the currentLogLevel variable was defined as a variable and it was set by 'setLogLevel()'.

```
    static void setLogLevel(LogLevel level)
    {
        getLogLevelRef() = level;
    }

    static LogLevel getCurrentLogLevel()
    {
        return getLogLevelRef();
    }

  static LogLevel& getLogLevelRef()
    {
        static auto currentLevel = static_cast<LogLevel>(1);
        return currentLevel;
    }
```

As the result, checkingLoggingLevel() is comparing with a variable (rather than const) and thus it could be used as a constexpr.

Now, I modified the code so that getCurrentLogLevel() is directly to use the compile-time evaluated value.

The latest patchset is now making it as 'constexpr'.

```
    constexpr static LogLevel getCurrentLogLevel()
    {
        return static_cast<LogLevel>(bmcwebLoggingLevel);
    }
```

The previous code saves log level as a member variable and then it is used to check again in Logger destructor.

But, as you pointed out, the 'log level' is not needed into the class, as Logger will be compiled into the binary only if needed based on the caller's side.

So, it will be like:

```
    Logger([[maybe_unused]] const std::string& prefix,
           [[maybe_unused]] const std::string& filename,
           [[maybe_unused]] const size_t line)
     {
           stringstream << ....;
     }

    ~Logger()
    {
           stringstream << std::endl;
           std::cerr << stringstream.str();
    }

    template <typename T>
    Logger& operator<<([[maybe_unused]] T const& value)
    {
        // Somewhere in the code we're implicitly casting an array to a
        // pointer in logging code. It's non-trivial to find,
        // so disable the check here for now
        // NOLINTNEXTLINE(cppcoreguidelines-pro-bounds-array-to-pointer-decay)
        stringstream << value;
        return *this;
    }

    And then

    #define BMCWEB_LOG_CRITICAL                                                \
    if constexpr (crow::Logger::checkLoggingLevel(crow::LogLevel::Critical))   \
    crow::Logger("CRITICAL", __FILE__, __LINE__)


```
